<doc id="206137" wikidata="Q1365748" url="?curid=206137" title="Spectrum (functional analysis)">
<text>In mathematics, particularly in functional analysis, the spectrum of a bounded linear operator (or, more generally, an unbounded linear operator) is a generalisation of the set of eigenvalues of a matrix. Specifically, a complex number formula_1 is said to be in the spectrum of a bounded linear operator formula_2 if formula_3

* either has &quot;no&quot; set-theoretic inverse;
* or the set-theoretic inverse is either unbounded or defined on a non-dense subset.

Here, formula_4 is the identity operator.

By the closed graph theorem, formula_1 is in the spectrum if and only if the bounded operator formula_6 is non-bijective on formula_7.

The study of spectra and related properties is known as &quot;spectral theory&quot;, which has numerous applications, most notably the mathematical formulation of quantum mechanics.

The spectrum of an operator on a finite-dimensional vector space is precisely the set of eigenvalues. However an operator on an infinite-dimensional space may have additional elements in its spectrum, and may have no eigenvalues. For example, consider the right shift operator &quot;R&quot; on the Hilbert space ℓ2,
:formula_8
This has no eigenvalues, since if &quot;Rx&quot;=&quot;λx&quot; then by expanding this expression we see that &quot;x&quot;1=0, &quot;x&quot;2=0, etc. On the other hand, 0 is in the spectrum because although the operator &quot;R&quot; − 0 (i.e. &quot;R&quot; itself) is invertible, the inverse is defined on a set which is not dense in ℓ2. In fact &quot;every&quot; bounded linear operator on a complex Banach space must have a non-empty spectrum.

The notion of spectrum extends to unbounded (i.e. not necessarily bounded) operators. A complex number &quot;λ&quot; is said to be in the spectrum of an unbounded operator formula_9 defined on domain formula_10 if there is no bounded inverse formula_11 defined on the whole of formula_12 If &quot;T&quot; is closed (which includes the case when &quot;T&quot; is bounded), boundedness of formula_13 follows automatically from its existence.

The space of bounded linear operators &quot;B&quot;(&quot;X&quot;) on a Banach space &quot;X&quot; is an example of a unital Banach algebra. Since the definition of the spectrum does not mention any properties of &quot;B&quot;(&quot;X&quot;) except those that any such algebra has, the notion of a spectrum may be generalised to this context by using the same definition verbatim.

==Spectrum of a bounded operator==

===Definition===
Let formula_2 be a bounded linear operator acting on a Banach space formula_15 over the complex scalar field formula_16, and formula_4 be the identity operator on formula_15. The spectrum of formula_2 is the set of all formula_20 for which the operator formula_3 does not have an inverse that is a bounded linear operator.

Since formula_3 is a linear operator, the inverse is linear if it exists; and, by the bounded inverse theorem, it is bounded. Therefore, the spectrum consists precisely of those scalars formula_1 for which formula_3 is not bijective.

The spectrum of a given operator formula_2 is often denoted formula_26, and its complement, the resolvent set, is denoted formula_27. (formula_28 is sometimes used to denote the spectral radius of formula_2)

===Relation to eigenvalues===

If formula_1 is an eigenvalue of formula_2, then the operator formula_3 is not one-to-one, and therefore its inverse formula_13 is not defined. However, the converse statement is not true: the operator formula_34 may not have an inverse, even if formula_1 is not an eigenvalue. Thus the spectrum of an operator always contains all its eigenvalues, but is not limited to them.

For example, consider the Hilbert space formula_36, that consists of all bi-infinite sequences of real numbers
:formula_37
that have a finite sum of squares formula_38. The bilateral shift operator formula_2 simply displaces every element of the sequence by one position; namely if formula_40 then formula_41 for every integer formula_42. The eigenvalue equation formula_43 has no nonzero solution in this space, since it implies that all the values formula_44 have the same absolute value (if formula_45) or are a geometric progression (if formula_46); either way, the sum of their squares would not be finite. However, the operator formula_3 is not invertible if formula_48. For example, the sequence formula_49 such that formula_50 is in formula_36; but there is no sequence formula_52 in formula_36 such that formula_54 (that is, formula_55 for all formula_42).

=== Basic properties ===

The spectrum of a bounded operator &quot;T&quot; is always a closed, bounded subset of the complex plane.

If the spectrum were empty, then the &quot;resolvent function&quot;

:formula_57

would be defined everywhere on the complex plane and bounded. But it can be shown that the resolvent function &quot;R&quot; is holomorphic on its domain. By the vector-valued version of Liouville&#x27;s theorem, this function is constant, thus everywhere zero as it is zero at infinity. This would be a contradiction.

The boundedness of the spectrum follows from the Neumann series expansion in &quot;λ&quot;; the spectrum &quot;σ&quot;(&quot;T&quot;) is bounded by ||&quot;T&quot;||. A similar result shows the closedness of the spectrum.

The bound ||&quot;T&quot;|| on the spectrum can be refined somewhat. The &quot;spectral radius&quot;, &quot;r&quot;(&quot;T&quot;), of &quot;T&quot; is the radius of the smallest circle in the complex plane which is centered at the origin and contains the spectrum &quot;σ&quot;(&quot;T&quot;) inside of it, i.e.

:formula_58, formula_59, with domain formula_60 has a discrete set of eigenvalues (the discrete spectrum formula_61, which in this case coincides with the point spectrum formula_62 since there are no eigenvalues embedded into the continuous spectrum) that can be computed by the Rydberg formula. Their corresponding eigenfunctions are called eigenstates, or the bound states. The result of the ionization process is described by the continuous part of the spectrum (the energy of the collision/ionization is not &quot;quantized&quot;), represented by formula_63 (it also coincides with the essential spectrum, formula_64).
==Spectrum of the adjoint operator==

Let &quot;X&quot; be a Banach space and formula_9 a closed linear operator with dense domain formula_66.
If &quot;X*&quot; is the dual space of &quot;X&quot;, and formula_67 is the hermitian adjoint of &quot;T&quot;, then

:formula_68

(T) = \overline{\sigma_{\mathrm{p}}(T^*)}&lt;/math&gt;. 

In particular, formula_69.}}

We also get formula_70 by the following argument: &quot;X&quot; embeds isometrically into &quot;X**&quot;. 
Therefore, for every non-zero element in the kernel of formula_3 there exists a non-zero element in &quot;X**&quot; which vanishes on formula_72. 
Thus formula_73 can not be dense.

Furthermore, if &quot;X&quot; is reflexive, we have formula_74.

==Spectra of particular classes of operators==

===Compact operators===

If &quot;T&quot; is a compact operator, or, more generally, an inessential operator, then it can be shown that the spectrum is countable, that zero is the only possible accumulation point, and that any nonzero &quot;λ&quot; in the spectrum is an eigenvalue.

===Quasinilpotent operators===

A bounded operator formula_75 is quasinilpotent if formula_76 as formula_77 (in other words, if the spectral radius of &quot;A&quot; equals zero). Such operators could equivalently be characterized by the condition

:formula_78

An example of such an operator is formula_79, formula_80 for formula_81.

===Self-adjoint operators===

If &quot;X&quot; is a Hilbert space and &quot;T&quot; is a self-adjoint operator (or, more generally, a normal operator), then a remarkable result known as the spectral theorem gives an analogue of the diagonalisation theorem for normal finite-dimensional operators (Hermitian matrices, for example).

For self-adjoint operators, one can use spectral measures to define a decomposition of the spectrum into absolutely continuous, pure point, and singular parts.

== Spectrum of a real operator ==

The definitions of the resolvent and spectrum can be extended to any continuous linear operator formula_2 acting on a Banach space formula_15 over the real field formula_84 (instead of the complex field formula_16) via its complexification formula_86. In this case we define the resolvent set formula_28 as the set of all formula_88 such that formula_89 is invertible as an operator acting on the complexified space formula_90; then we define formula_91.

=== Real spectrum ===

The &quot;real spectrum&quot; of a continuous linear operator formula_2 acting on a real Banach space formula_15, denoted formula_94, is defined as the set of all formula_95 for which formula_3 fails to be invertible in the real algebra of bounded linear operators acting on formula_15. In this case we have formula_98. Note that the real spectrum may or may not coincide with the complex spectrum. In particular, the real spectrum could be empty.

== Spectrum of a unital Banach algebra ==

Let &quot;B&quot; be a complex Banach algebra containing a unit &quot;e&quot;. Then we define the spectrum &quot;σ&quot;(&quot;x&quot;) (or more explicitly &quot;σ&quot;&quot;B&quot;(&quot;x&quot;)) of an element &quot;x&quot; of &quot;B&quot; to be the set of those complex numbers &quot;λ&quot; for which &quot;λe&quot; − &quot;x&quot; is not invertible in &quot;B&quot;. This extends the definition for bounded linear operators &quot;B&quot;(&quot;X&quot;) on a Banach space &quot;X&quot;, since &quot;B&quot;(&quot;X&quot;) is a unital Banach algebra.

